@node "Requirements" "What do you need to use it ?"

To use ps2pk Amiga version (SMps2pk port) you need:

- An Amiga with at least OSV2.04

- PasTeXV1.4 (did not try V1.3, try it yourself)

- LaTeX2e and the fontinst package for creating the vpl files

- vptovf to create the tfm files (distributed with dvips)

@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation of ps2pk"

These are excerpts from the INSTALLATION files (partly deleted and adapted
to the paths I use in the binary distribution). I've added notes in brackets
where it was necessary. See Usage for general PasTeX1.4 usage.

V1.4:

(January 1994)

 1) Installing (Note: Additional information)

    Copy all the wanted binaries from bin to tex:bin (or mf:bin if you
    prefer that). Look at the overview wich purpose have the different
    programs. You can also install the doc files, though they are Unix
    manual pages and are not very readable (in the doc drawer). I recommand
    you to install this guide instead in your doc drawer (e.g. HELP:)

 2) Testing ps2pk 
    The directory Utopia contains the Utopia-Regular font donated by
    Adobe. To make from this type1 font a PKfile next steps are needed:
         setenv T1INPUTS /Utopia		(C-shell)
         (assuming you are in the bin directory)
         ps2pk -v -X300 Utopia-Regular.pfa      (long)
     or: ps2pk -v Utopia-Regular.pfa            (short using defaults)

    This will create the Utopia-Regular10.300pk font with the default
    AdobeStandard characters derived from ../Utopia/Utopia-Regular.afm.
    (The -v flag will show what the program is doing and which character
    codes are generated.)

    To see how for example the `Q' is rendered by ps2pk (using the IBM
    type1 rendering software) you can use:
         pk2bm -bcQ Utopia-Regular10.300pk

    Ps2pk has some extra options. All options are explained in the manual page
    (man/ps2pk.1). Here are the most important:
       -X<xres>	     the desired X-resolution (ex: 300, 329, 360, 432, etc)
       -E<expansion> the factor to expand a font
       -S<slant>     to get a slanted font.
    
 3) Using Utopia-Regular with dvips.
    Before you can run dvips to generate the PostScript output that can
    be printed you have to make the font available to dvips by adding a
    line to psfonts.map (normally located in /usr/local/lib/tex/ps).
    This line tells dvips if a font is resident (available in the
    printer) and if not how to download it. For rputr we need to add 
    next line in psfonts.map (the new version of afm2tfm will show this
    line on the standard output):
       rputr Utopia-Regular
    
    and to copy or to move Utopia-Regular to /usr/local/lib/tex/ps so
    that it will be downloaded (added to the PostScript output).
       dvips testfont
    
    If you have GhostScript, and your dvips is installed so that it does
    not send the output immediately to the printer, you can check 
    testfont.ps behind your X-display with:
       gs testfont.ps

 4) Using rputr.300pk with dvips.
    You have to remove the line you have added to psfonts.map. Then
    dvips will try to find a PK-font instead of the type1 font.
    
 5) Automatic font generation with MakeTeXPK.

    If you are interested in automatically generating PK fonts from
    either METAFONT and/or type1 sources you may want to install the
    MTPK package. This package provides a perl script that allows
    DVI drivers to generate missing PK sizes in a platform independant
    way. See ftp.urc.tue.nl:pub/tex/MTPK??.gtz and the MTPK??.README
    file for more information (under development).

 6) Although ps2pk is set up for AdobeStandardEncoding, the default used 
    by current versions of dvips, it will also accept other PostScript
    and TeX encodings. An interesting alternative for TeX users is the new
    TUG 8bits font standard (see: TUGboat #10 vol. 4 1990). This standard
    is a superset of ISOLatin1 with many accented characters. The PostScript
    encoding used by this new font is contained in etc/EC.enc. In order to
    use it you will need afm2tfm version 7.0 (distributed with dvips5485++).

    [Here you should read two danger bends!! Next in small letters . . .

    As an example how an encoding scheme other than Adobe Standard can
    be used we show how you can use the Utopia-Regular font as an
    extended Computer Modern font. We use this encoding scheme both on
    the TeX input side (let us call that internal encoding) and on the
    TeX output side (we will call that external encoding). It is clear
    that we can not use the plain macros that are still based on
    oldstyle 7bits internal encodings.  But we can use NFSS-DC a new
    font selection scheme based on DC encodings. The DC encoding is a
    preliminar version of the EC encoding.
    
    How do we generate the appropriate TFM, VF and PK files?
      rputr.300pk:
         setenv T1INPUTS Utopia			(C-shell)
         ps2pk -e etc/EC.enc Utopia-Regular rputr.300pk
      rputr.tfm and putr.vpl:
         afm2tfm Utopia/Utopia-Regular.afm -p etc/EC.enc -v putr.vpl rputr.tfm
      putr.vf putr.tfm:
         vptovf putr.vpl putr.vf putr.tfm
    
    How do we use it?
      psfonts.map (add line):
         rputr Utopia-Regular " ECEncoding ReEncodeFont " <EC.enc
      $TEXCONFIG:
         install here Utopia-Regular and EC.enc
      testfont.tex (tex-nfss-dc is a special plain TeX version):
         tex-nfss-dc testfont (choose `putr' and '\bigtest\bye')
         xdvi testfont
         dvips testfont.
    
    . . .End of dangerous stuff and the small letters]

V1.5:

 1) Installing (Note: Additional information)

    Copy all the wanted binaries from bin to tex:bin (or mf:bin if you
    prefer that). Look at the overview wich purpose have the different
    programs. You can also install the doc files, though they are Unix
    manual pages and are not very readable (in the doc drawer). I recommand
    you to install this guide instead in your doc drawer (e.g. HELP:)

    Warning: V1.5 is still in beta stage and may contain bugs. Best is
    to keep the old binaries under ps2pk14 or similar until they get
    superfluous in the final release.    

 2) Testing ps2pk from ps2pk directory. 
    The directory PSources contains the Utopia-Regular font donated by
    Adobe. To make from this type1 font a PKfile next steps are needed:
         setenv T1INPUTS /PSources 		  (C-shell)
         (assuming you are in the bin directory)
         ps2pk -v Utopia-Regular.pfa

    This will create the Utopia-Regular10.300pk font with the default
    AdobeStandard characters derived from ../PSources/Utopia-Regular.afm.
    (The -v flag will show what the program is doing and which character
    codes are generated.)

    To see how for example the `Q' is rendered by ps2pk (using the IBM
    type1 rendering software) you can use:
         pk2bm -bcQ Utopia-Regular10.300pk
    
    Ps2pk has some extra options. All options are explained in the manual
    page (ps2pk.1). Here are the most important:
       -X<xres>	     the desired X-resolution (ex: 300, 329, 360, 432, etc)
       -E<expansion> the factor to expand a font
       -S<slant>     to get a slanted font.

 3) Automatic font generation

    Note by the port author: I personally tend to change the CALLMF
    rexx scripts so they call ps2pk if there is no corresponding
    .mf-file found for your font.

    This version of ps2pk comes with mtpk an automatic PK font
    generator written in C (derived from an earlier perl script)
    and pkfonts a front-end that can generate missing fonts from
    DVI files. Both programs use the same configuration file
    (mtpk.cfg). The following steps can be used to test and install
    these programs. See the manual sections of mtpk for more details.

      3.1) go to the mtpk directory, adapt the configuration file
	   mtpk.cfg to your TeX defaults and try `maketest'. The test
	   expects the new version of ps2pk in your PATH.

           This should install a test version of mtpk and pkfonts.
	   These versions are then used to create a TeX font for
	   Utopia-Regular which is available in PSources.

      3.2) Test if mtpk works with METAFONT (check the value of
	   MFINPUTS in mtpk.cfg) by trying to make cmr10.331pk

		mtpk -v cmr10 331 300

      3.3) Test gsftopk (check gsfontmap in mtpk.cfg) and try

		mtpk ptmr0 331 300
      
      (Note: I don't know if there is an gsftopk port for Amiga, but
      I have the sources and I will try to compile it somewhen)
	
      3.4) If you install ps2pk you probably have good quality
	   type1 fonts. To use them with mtpk you need to install
	   a PSres.upr resource database on the place defined in
	   the Makefile with mkpsres (directory PSres). All type1
	   fonts, AFM files and encoding vectors available on your
	   system should be added to this resource database. If
	   your workstation comes with Display PostScript (DPS)
	   a good place to install your PostScript resources is in
	   the directory used by DPS (see manual of mkpsres).

	   Try to make ptmr0.332pk with ps2pk

		mtpk ptmr0 332 300

      3.5) install mtpk and pkfonts

	   Change the path for MTPKCFG in the Makefile to its final
	   destination BEFORE installing.
	   
	   (Note: the amiga binary contains a path for tex:config)

	   Adapt the definitions in mtpk.cfg to its final values.

	   Decide what pseudo-user you want to use for installing PK
	   fonts in public directories. Create this usercode and change
	   all PK directories to this new owner (you need superuser
	   priviledges). You can also make the public directories world
	   writable if you prefer.

      (Note: unimportant for Amiga Version, no MultiUser parts integrated)

      3.6) Recompile your DVI drivers (dvips and xdvi) so that they will
	   use mtpk automatically. You can also use pkfonts to generate PK
	   fonts from a DVI file.

      (Note: I don't know much about the amiga port of dvips, read there
      for more information if you can go around this problem)

	   Add \usepackage{times} to a copy of sample2e.tex and make
	   all missing PK fonts with:

		pkfonts sample2e[.dvi]

           Or just check which fonts are used

		pkfonts -a sample2e

           or are missing

		pkfonts -m sample2e

Good luck!
 
@endnode

@node "overview" "Overview over the different binaries"

ps2pk V1.4 contains of the following programs:

  - ps2pk	a program to build PK fonts from PostScript type1 fonts
  - pk2bm	a program that allows to look at a PK character.
  - CreatePKFont a primitive skript which creates your pk fonts similar  
                 to the CALLMF MakeTexFont.rexx ARexx skript.
  - pktest  a program to demonstrate how a PK file can be created from
            a single character bitmap
  - mag     a tool to calculate fontsizes given magsteps
  - pfb2pfa a program to convert a type1 pfb (binary) file into a pfa (ASCII)

There is also included the type1 library. It is a link library for SAS/C.
It should be possible to make a real type1.library out of it, but I was
too lazy to do it (under Unix it is a shared lib I think)

ps2pk V1.5 contains of the following programs:

  - ps2pk	a program to build PK fonts from PostScript type1 fonts
  - pk2bm	a program that allows to look at a PK character.
  - misc drawer:
    * basename: reimplementation of BSD's basename (testing common.lib)
    * lspsres: test program for psres.lib (path problems may occur here)
    * mag: see above
    * pfb2pfa: see above
    * psargs: test program to test functions /mtpk/psinfo.c psinfo.c is not
      included in the binary distribution)
    * psearch: test program to test recursive search
    * sexpr: tests strexpr() function from common.lib
  - mtpk drawer:
    * mtpk: program to generate missing PK font (will this make CALLMF scripts
      superfluous ? Give me your comments!)
    * pkfonts: program to generate missing PK font from dvifiles
  - mkpsres a program to build postscript resource database file.

Also I included the link libraries (type1.lib is unchanged in V1.5 so it is
only found in ps2pk14 directory) common.lib and psres.lib. See above for
more (similar) information about the link libraries.

@endnode

@node "PTUsage" "PasTeXV1.4 Usage"

How to use PostScript fonts with PasTeXV1.4
-------------------------------------------

Attention: all information here is related to the V1.4 release.

I've compiled the program nearly a year ago but thought it was not useable
because PasTeX does not support virtual font. In fact it could do it but I
did not understand how to use it correctly (using T1 encoding). I only tried
the standard encoding and gave up because I got none of the german 'umlauts'.
Meanwhile I succeded in using Garamond PS font with the T1 encoding and I
also understand how why it works :-).

Starting from the beginning: You must have installed PasTeX1.4 (I did not try
V1.3 but I see no reason why it should not work there (except of an old
metafont program perhabs) and most importand you need to have installed
LaTeX2e to be able to use all the characters of a particulary font.

At first you need to install the fontinst package (avalaible on CTAN in the
fonts/utilities/fontinst directory) and create an example font (read the
fontinst docs). Of course you need to install an ps font and the corresponding
.afm files. Defaults for afm are tex:afm and tex:ps for .pbf/.pfa fonts.

If you have created the .vpl file(s) with the fontinst package you need to
create a tfm file for your font at first. I use the vptovf program which
is able to create not only the virtual font but also the tfm file needed
by it. Insted of using virtual fonts (in dvips it would be possible but not
with showdvi or dviprint) you use ps2pk to create the pk files.

Now you should be able to create your document. To acces all characters of a
PS font you need to enbale T1 encoding with \usepackage[T1]{fontenc}. You
must include the .sty file of your wanted font (e.g. \usepackage{times}).
For german umlauts you need to include \usepackage[latin1]{inputenc}, too.

In the examples drawer is a tex file which prints all symbol of a font.
The only thing you need to change is the "times" style file and replace
it with the style file of your font.

Now you can latex your document. Normally if you call showdvi know it tries
to generate your font using a CALLMF ARexx script (which will fail obviously).
I would recommand this only if you do not know the name of the pk file which
needs to be created. Assuming you know the font name now you can create the
missing PK file using ps2pk. You need to have installed the EC.enc file
from the etc directory to your tex:ps drawer. Then you can call my simple
CreatePKFont script which calls itself ps2pk.

The script assumes the following:
- the postscript font (*.pfb or .pfa) is in the tex:ps drawer
- the EC.enc file is in the tex:ps drawer
- the afm file is in the tex:afm drawer
- the pk files are in the tex:pk directory

I recommand you to edit the file and adapt the file to your installation.
The script accepts the following parameters:
NAME/A,DESTNAME,DEST/A,hbasedpi/A,vbasedpi/A,magstep

NAME is the file of the postscript font without .pfb or .pfa
DESTNAME is the name ot the pk font name without .<size>pk (e.g. if the font
         you want to create is ptrmq.100pk you type in ptmrq)
DEST is the directory of the output device you create the pk file for
     (I use e.g. PV for ShowDVI and HPdj for dviprint on HP printers)
     It adds the size drawer automatically to the device directory.
hbasedpi,vbasedpi: Same as the dpi's from the MakeTeXFont script (i.e. the
     size/solution of the pk file)
magstep: the magnification of the font (not used by the script :-). That means
     that you need to give the scaled dpi as hbase/vbase and not the base itself.

Example: CreatePKFont ptmr ptmrq HPdj 300 300 0 creates an pk font for ptmr at
         with 300 dpi solution (i.e. for HP Deskjet).

The script creates the resulting pk files directly in the corresponding pk
directory so you need not to copy it by yourself. It also overwrites old
files without warning.

Having created the pk file(s) you can now watch your dvi files with showdvi or
print them using dviprint. Have fun and good luck!

Attention: Without further handling of the pk files showdvi will warn you about
incorrect checksums. I have not yet taken a look into this problem but I know
it is (partially at least) solved. Look in the fonts2e drawer for closer
information (this will probably get superfluous in the V1.5 release)

@endnode

